<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="11" pageNumber="212" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1895,2029]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1932,1957]" pageId="11" pageNumber="212">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Frons unmarked, varying from pale to entirely dark, or with darkened muscle arcs. Frons large, in profile projecting below plane of clypellus; ocelli absent. Pronotum steeply declivous. Tegminal venation absent or indicated only by colour pattern with numerous nearly parallel veinlets in tips. Tegmina short and strongly convex, twice as long as broad or shorter. Hindwings absent, or with costa slightly produced as low, rounded basal lobe, armed with 
<number box="[284,326,188,212]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
fine hairlike spines directed outwards (
<figureCitation box="[767,835,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1584,1606]" captionTargetBox="[276,1312,273,1556]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[265,1321,267,1560]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. New World Orthoraphini: habitus (A – B), hind wing (C – F) including detail of hamuli on costal margin (G – H), male abdomen in ventral aspect (J) and male genital capsule in lateral aspect (K). A, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) frontalis (Stål); B, F, H, O. cassidioides Westwood, female; C, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) obliqua (Jacobi); D, Orthorapha (Balsania) concinna (Stål); E, G, Orthorapha (Balsania) geminata (Jacobi); J, K, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) bufo (Walker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217115/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[820,835,188,212]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
H), narrow with venation weak, most apparent at tips; fold between forks of Cu deep and anal lobe narrow (
<figureCitation box="[747,814,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1584,1606]" captionTargetBox="[276,1312,273,1556]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[265,1321,267,1560]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. New World Orthoraphini: habitus (A – B), hind wing (C – F) including detail of hamuli on costal margin (G – H), male abdomen in ventral aspect (J) and male genital capsule in lateral aspect (K). A, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) frontalis (Stål); B, F, H, O. cassidioides Westwood, female; C, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) obliqua (Jacobi); D, Orthorapha (Balsania) concinna (Stål); E, G, Orthorapha (Balsania) geminata (Jacobi); J, K, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) bufo (Walker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217115/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[799,814,224,248]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
F). 
<collectingCountry box="[852,908,223,248]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">Hind</collectingCountry>
basitarsomere hirsute on lower surface (except in 
<taxonomicName box="[180,292,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Aphrophoridae" genus="Orthorapha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invidia" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[180,292,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">O. invidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[299,388,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[299,388,260,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,392]" box="[199,556,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,401,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">Included species.</emphasis>
Four species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="213" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">Remarks.</emphasis>
The narrow hindwings with reduced wing-coupling hooks suggests that even fully winged individuals are flightless.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
